1
00:00:06,147 --> 00:00:06,907
I guess we get started.

2
00:00:06,947 --> 00:00:07,628
Good morning, everybody.

3
00:00:07,868 --> 00:00:08,488
Thank you for coming.

4
00:00:09,509 --> 00:00:10,690
My name is Sven Vincke.

5
00:00:10,710 --> 00:00:13,072
I'm the founder and director of Larian Studios.

6
00:00:13,993 --> 00:00:15,734
And so today I'll tell you a little bit about

7
00:00:16,194 --> 00:00:17,655
the making of Divinity Original Sin 2

8
00:00:18,196 --> 00:00:21,238
and the bruises we obtained while we were making it.

9
00:00:22,639 --> 00:00:25,021
To start, I'll give you a very, very quick history

10
00:00:25,041 --> 00:00:26,822
of Larian, just to give you some context

11
00:00:26,862 --> 00:00:29,064
for the decisions we made and the environment

12
00:00:29,104 --> 00:00:30,225
in which things were taking place.

13
00:00:31,166 --> 00:00:32,246
We've been making RPGs since 97.

14
00:00:33,645 --> 00:00:36,186
And our history can be split in two parts.

15
00:00:36,246 --> 00:00:38,987
There's the part before 2010, and there's a part after 2010.

16
00:00:39,247 --> 00:00:42,168
And the part before 2010 was the part

17
00:00:42,208 --> 00:00:44,809
where we depended on external funding to fund our projects.

18
00:00:44,829 --> 00:00:46,510
So typically, those were publishers,

19
00:00:46,550 --> 00:00:47,690
but there was also work for hire.

20
00:00:48,210 --> 00:00:51,051
And post-2010, we took our fate in our own hands,

21
00:00:51,311 --> 00:00:54,132
and we started making, we started

22
00:00:54,172 --> 00:00:55,193
self-publishing our games.

23
00:00:56,100 --> 00:00:58,241
And so Larin has always been a company

24
00:00:58,441 --> 00:01:01,062
that tried to reach for the sky and often crashed,

25
00:01:01,282 --> 00:01:03,003
and that's where all the bruises come from.

26
00:01:03,764 --> 00:01:05,245
But we never gave up, we kept on trying,

27
00:01:05,685 --> 00:01:08,866
and that has led to, I have to say,

28
00:01:08,947 --> 00:01:10,487
a very successful last five years.

29
00:01:11,428 --> 00:01:13,609
But we feel we earned it because the first 15 years

30
00:01:13,649 --> 00:01:15,270
were very complicated.

31
00:01:16,010 --> 00:01:19,032
So in 2014, we launched a game called Divinity Original Sin 1.

32
00:01:20,053 --> 00:01:21,613
It was very successful, it was a Kickstarter game.

33
00:01:22,194 --> 00:01:24,694
We raised $1 million on Kickstarter.

34
00:01:25,415 --> 00:01:27,175
Game sold really well, had a high Metacritic,

35
00:01:27,215 --> 00:01:28,395
was GameSpot's Game of the Year.

36
00:01:29,356 --> 00:01:31,717
It sold, I think, 2.5 million units by now,

37
00:01:31,797 --> 00:01:32,997
so we're very happy about that.

38
00:01:33,797 --> 00:01:37,298
And it essentially gave us the rocket fuel

39
00:01:37,318 --> 00:01:39,379
that we needed to finally reach for the sky

40
00:01:39,619 --> 00:01:42,260
and not try to crash on the ground.

41
00:01:43,360 --> 00:01:44,781
But before we could do that,

42
00:01:45,781 --> 00:01:47,061
we had to solve a few problems.

43
00:01:47,902 --> 00:01:54,124
So after Original Sin 1, we came with the brilliant idea of making Original Sin 2.

44
00:01:54,425 --> 00:01:56,125
It was a very hard decision to make.

45
00:01:57,106 --> 00:01:59,527
And we said this one is going to be the big one.

46
00:01:59,547 --> 00:02:01,848
This is going to be the most ambitious game that we've ever made.

47
00:02:02,448 --> 00:02:07,771
And we are going to show the world that we always had it in ourselves to make brilliant RPGs.

48
00:02:08,909 --> 00:02:10,491
To do that, we needed a much bigger team.

49
00:02:11,031 --> 00:02:13,134
And one of the problems that we had been having

50
00:02:13,554 --> 00:02:15,416
was that the cost of living and of wages

51
00:02:15,657 --> 00:02:17,579
in the country where we started, which was Belgium,

52
00:02:17,879 --> 00:02:18,560
was very high.

53
00:02:18,840 --> 00:02:20,482
And when we looked, for instance, to the east,

54
00:02:20,522 --> 00:02:22,925
we saw that some of our colleagues

55
00:02:23,025 --> 00:02:26,228
had wages that were almost half of what we were paying.

56
00:02:26,328 --> 00:02:29,091
So that basically meant that they could have two developers

57
00:02:29,131 --> 00:02:29,732
for us, one.

58
00:02:30,839 --> 00:02:32,340
And another problem that we've been struggling with

59
00:02:32,440 --> 00:02:33,920
was that of crunch.

60
00:02:34,141 --> 00:02:35,301
As we were reaching for the sky,

61
00:02:35,341 --> 00:02:38,783
we often had to fix problems that appeared out of thin air

62
00:02:38,843 --> 00:02:40,883
and we needed to fix them and we were a small team,

63
00:02:40,943 --> 00:02:43,024
so that meant that we had to crunch a lot.

64
00:02:43,044 --> 00:02:44,265
So we tried to get rid of that.

65
00:02:44,945 --> 00:02:46,746
And another problem that we had to solve was

66
00:02:48,267 --> 00:02:52,272
we needed access to senior talent because in Belgium there's not much of a mature games

67
00:02:52,333 --> 00:02:57,981
industry at least back then there wasn't and we needed people that actually had done productions

68
00:02:58,081 --> 00:03:02,467
had shipped many games and we couldn't find them or if we found them it was very expensive to bring

69
00:03:02,487 --> 00:03:02,827
them over.

70
00:03:03,829 --> 00:03:05,350
So, the answer was obvious.

71
00:03:06,051 --> 00:03:11,436
We started looking outwards to other countries and we'd been working with a small studio

72
00:03:11,616 --> 00:03:14,939
in St. Petersburg in Russia who had helped us with the Mac port of Divinity Original

73
00:03:14,959 --> 00:03:18,863
Sin 1 and we approached them and we asked them, would you guys mind growing a little

74
00:03:18,883 --> 00:03:21,986
bit because we could use some help and they said yes.

75
00:03:22,767 --> 00:03:24,767
And so that's how Larin St. Petersburg was born.

76
00:03:25,508 --> 00:03:27,388
And then we started thinking about

77
00:03:27,448 --> 00:03:29,629
how can we solve this crunch problem?

78
00:03:29,749 --> 00:03:32,190
And the idea popped up that if you were capable

79
00:03:32,230 --> 00:03:34,111
of organizing your processes one way or another,

80
00:03:34,231 --> 00:03:36,291
that you could basically offload the work

81
00:03:36,311 --> 00:03:38,292
that you had finished at five o'clock in the evening

82
00:03:38,692 --> 00:03:41,273
and send it to another time zone and they could start,

83
00:03:41,353 --> 00:03:43,634
because for them it was the morning, working on that.

84
00:03:43,854 --> 00:03:46,275
Maybe you could have a longer production line per day

85
00:03:46,655 --> 00:03:50,457
without having people to work continuously.

86
00:03:50,897 --> 00:03:52,137
And that's how Larin Quebec was born.

87
00:03:52,837 --> 00:03:53,998
And then we had one last problem,

88
00:03:54,018 --> 00:03:55,359
which I didn't mention that we needed to solve,

89
00:03:55,399 --> 00:03:56,559
is we needed a lot of writers.

90
00:03:57,320 --> 00:04:00,001
English is not my native language, as you can hear,

91
00:04:01,302 --> 00:04:02,823
and it was hard to find writers for us.

92
00:04:02,883 --> 00:04:04,344
So we started looking at the UK,

93
00:04:04,404 --> 00:04:06,845
which was the closest country

94
00:04:06,985 --> 00:04:08,266
where people were speaking English,

95
00:04:09,066 --> 00:04:10,267
and we ended up in Dublin,

96
00:04:11,007 --> 00:04:14,689
where we started a small office with nine writers,

97
00:04:14,989 --> 00:04:17,471
and where we also decided to put our publishing team,

98
00:04:17,511 --> 00:04:18,971
because we were self-publishing.

99
00:04:19,532 --> 00:04:26,983
And like this we ended up with four studios out of a small studio of 40 people in Ghent within the space of a year.

100
00:04:28,444 --> 00:04:30,685
So all of this happened between September 2014

101
00:04:31,905 --> 00:04:32,845
and February 2015.

102
00:04:33,245 --> 00:04:38,007
And so while the Quebec and Dublin teams were being set up,

103
00:04:38,247 --> 00:04:40,227
the team in Ghent and the team in St. Petersburg

104
00:04:40,267 --> 00:04:42,108
started working on Divinity Original Sin 1,

105
00:04:42,908 --> 00:04:46,149
the enhanced edition for PS4 and Xbox One.

106
00:04:46,849 --> 00:04:49,069
And so the idea was that each of these teams

107
00:04:50,110 --> 00:04:51,830
that we set up were basically going to be clones

108
00:04:51,890 --> 00:04:52,710
or mirrors of each other,

109
00:04:53,151 --> 00:04:56,251
so that you could literally pass work on as the sun rose.

110
00:04:58,393 --> 00:05:01,155
And that was not the easiest thing in the world to set up,

111
00:05:01,536 --> 00:05:03,838
and it took a lot of time, but it started working,

112
00:05:03,858 --> 00:05:05,179
and we'll see some examples of that.

113
00:05:06,140 --> 00:05:09,644
So by May 2015, we had teams that were operational

114
00:05:09,664 --> 00:05:10,384
in Quebec and Dublin.

115
00:05:11,565 --> 00:05:12,887
The guys in Ghent and St. Petersburg

116
00:05:12,927 --> 00:05:14,128
were working on Enhanced Edition,

117
00:05:14,748 --> 00:05:17,691
and so it was time to start working on Original Sin 2.

118
00:05:18,132 --> 00:05:20,574
And so it was the Quebec team who had actually

119
00:05:20,594 --> 00:05:21,875
never worked on the Original Sin game.

120
00:05:22,535 --> 00:05:24,776
and the Dublin team, which was full of new writers,

121
00:05:25,157 --> 00:05:26,237
that were going to lead the charge.

122
00:05:26,277 --> 00:05:27,738
And they started working on a small demo,

123
00:05:28,218 --> 00:05:29,999
which was produced in three to four months,

124
00:05:30,099 --> 00:05:32,400
which was going to showcase the pillars

125
00:05:32,680 --> 00:05:33,900
of Divinity Original Sin 2,

126
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:36,441
and which we were going to use to show to press,

127
00:05:36,521 --> 00:05:38,222
to the community, what we wanted to make,

128
00:05:38,502 --> 00:05:40,743
and which we wanted to also take to Kickstarter.

129
00:05:41,564 --> 00:05:46,346
And so the idea was that when the teams that were working on Original Sin 1 for PS4 and

130
00:05:46,406 --> 00:05:51,649
X1 were finished, they would then roll into the production that had been set up with the

131
00:05:51,730 --> 00:05:52,890
Original Sin 2 demo.

132
00:05:54,425 --> 00:05:59,691
So the core pillars of Original Sin 2 were that we wanted to have a better story.

133
00:05:59,971 --> 00:06:03,755
We got a lot of flack for the story in Original Sin 1, so we were frustrated by that and so

134
00:06:03,776 --> 00:06:04,676
we wanted to fix that.

135
00:06:05,237 --> 00:06:06,959
We also wanted to improve the combat.

136
00:06:07,339 --> 00:06:12,985
We got a lot of flack over the combat, especially from our hardcore community, after the beginning

137
00:06:13,005 --> 00:06:15,108
of the game, so as we went into Act 2 and Act 3.

138
00:06:16,490 --> 00:06:21,542
We also found that our modding plans that we had for Original Sin 1 hadn't been that successful,

139
00:06:21,562 --> 00:06:25,030
and dominantly because we hadn't really supported it well, so we wanted to fix that.

140
00:06:25,800 --> 00:06:28,202
We also wanted to have a higher degree of polish

141
00:06:28,242 --> 00:06:29,463
because we thought that the gameplay

142
00:06:29,483 --> 00:06:31,764
that we were presenting could be consumed

143
00:06:31,804 --> 00:06:33,325
by a lot more players than actually had

144
00:06:33,365 --> 00:06:34,266
play original Sin 1.

145
00:06:35,006 --> 00:06:37,608
And multiplayer was one of the big innovations

146
00:06:37,648 --> 00:06:40,070
of original Sin 1 in the narrative RPG space,

147
00:06:40,430 --> 00:06:42,651
so we wanted to bring more multiplayer options.

148
00:06:43,312 --> 00:06:44,973
And so all of these things translated

149
00:06:44,993 --> 00:06:48,435
in the following big axis of development.

150
00:06:49,616 --> 00:06:51,197
We needed a more gripping story,

151
00:06:51,377 --> 00:06:53,078
one that was going to captivate you

152
00:06:53,118 --> 00:06:53,959
all the way until the end.

153
00:06:54,520 --> 00:06:57,665
We needed a new style of writing so that people would see,

154
00:06:57,745 --> 00:06:59,387
okay, well, they mean it when they're talking

155
00:06:59,427 --> 00:07:00,149
about a better story.

156
00:07:01,329 --> 00:07:05,192
We introduced what became known as the origin stories,

157
00:07:05,332 --> 00:07:08,214
which was essentially the ability to role play characters

158
00:07:08,234 --> 00:07:10,696
who had a set background, a set story,

159
00:07:10,716 --> 00:07:12,898
a different sets of quests within the world.

160
00:07:13,698 --> 00:07:15,140
And we introduced a tag system,

161
00:07:15,220 --> 00:07:17,682
which was essentially, if you played Dungeons & Dragons,

162
00:07:17,702 --> 00:07:18,703
then you know what a background is.

163
00:07:18,743 --> 00:07:20,724
It was essentially a background that you got in the game.

164
00:07:21,165 --> 00:07:22,646
And then whenever you talk to somebody,

165
00:07:22,706 --> 00:07:24,487
they would recognize that you had that background

166
00:07:24,547 --> 00:07:25,788
and they would react as if you.

167
00:07:27,051 --> 00:07:27,733
were that person.

168
00:07:27,953 --> 00:07:31,322
And these were very important features

169
00:07:31,342 --> 00:07:33,328
that we were introducing to those two.

170
00:07:34,414 --> 00:07:35,595
Another thing we wanted to do is,

171
00:07:36,095 --> 00:07:37,656
we felt that in Original Sin 2,

172
00:07:37,716 --> 00:07:39,917
our action point economy was ruined

173
00:07:40,017 --> 00:07:41,398
because we had way too much action points,

174
00:07:41,418 --> 00:07:42,758
so we wanted to be much tighter.

175
00:07:43,219 --> 00:07:44,519
And this came from a philosophy

176
00:07:44,559 --> 00:07:46,681
that we wanted each point, anything that you,

177
00:07:47,221 --> 00:07:49,362
every single level up point that you used

178
00:07:49,702 --> 00:07:52,363
to feel important so that you would care about it.

179
00:07:53,544 --> 00:07:56,025
And we also wanted to change the armor system,

180
00:07:56,226 --> 00:07:57,846
over which we got an enormous amount of flak.

181
00:07:57,906 --> 00:07:59,067
We'll talk about that a little bit later.

182
00:08:00,028 --> 00:08:02,609
the armor system, which was very unclear in Original Sin 1,

183
00:08:02,790 --> 00:08:04,551
and which we wanted to make a lot clearer

184
00:08:04,671 --> 00:08:05,432
in Original Sin 2.

185
00:08:06,552 --> 00:08:09,955
We also wanted to tie the story to the narrative mechanics

186
00:08:10,035 --> 00:08:11,976
that were being produced in the game.

187
00:08:12,076 --> 00:08:14,238
So we felt the game was so large

188
00:08:14,318 --> 00:08:16,880
that you needed to have a continuous stream

189
00:08:16,940 --> 00:08:18,361
of new mechanics coming towards you

190
00:08:18,381 --> 00:08:19,882
to motivate you to continue playing,

191
00:08:20,342 --> 00:08:21,883
and we wanted those mechanics to be present

192
00:08:21,944 --> 00:08:23,905
at every single spot in the game world

193
00:08:24,025 --> 00:08:24,986
and indeed in the story.

194
00:08:26,136 --> 00:08:29,137
And then to top it off, we wanted to have PvP multiplayer,

195
00:08:29,157 --> 00:08:31,318
or at least the option of having PvP multiplayer

196
00:08:31,398 --> 00:08:32,438
while you were playing the game.

197
00:08:32,898 --> 00:08:36,020
And this came from the idea that the core story

198
00:08:36,060 --> 00:08:38,621
was going to be something that was similar to Highlander

199
00:08:38,661 --> 00:08:40,081
in which there could be only one,

200
00:08:40,381 --> 00:08:41,902
although we didn't know at that particular time

201
00:08:41,942 --> 00:08:43,442
what the only one was going to be.

202
00:08:43,683 --> 00:08:45,843
And we'll see that that was also a big problem.

203
00:08:47,159 --> 00:08:51,342
And then finally, we wanted to have updated graphics,

204
00:08:51,442 --> 00:08:53,604
obviously, a more realistic visual style.

205
00:08:54,104 --> 00:08:57,606
And as I said, we wanted to take modding into account

206
00:08:57,647 --> 00:08:59,348
from the get-go, because adding modding

207
00:08:59,528 --> 00:09:01,029
after the fact is very complicated.

208
00:09:01,049 --> 00:09:03,791
But if you take it into your development pipeline

209
00:09:03,851 --> 00:09:06,353
when you start, in general it should work.

210
00:09:07,520 --> 00:09:10,083
So the Kickstarter demo was really successful.

211
00:09:10,644 --> 00:09:13,448
We made our million dollars in 12 hours,

212
00:09:13,929 --> 00:09:14,910
or in the first day, sorry,

213
00:09:15,271 --> 00:09:16,533
and we reached our goal within 12 hours.

214
00:09:17,746 --> 00:09:22,050
And so we were excited by that because obviously it meant that the direction that we had shown

215
00:09:22,110 --> 00:09:27,334
to our community was appreciated and they wanted us to continue on that road.

216
00:09:27,894 --> 00:09:33,179
And because we hadn't expected it was going to go that fast, we really hadn't prepared

217
00:09:33,219 --> 00:09:36,221
our stretch goals properly, but we said, you know what, we'll just take those core pillars

218
00:09:36,662 --> 00:09:38,443
and we'll build our stretch goals around that.

219
00:09:39,299 --> 00:09:41,099
And so this is how these strategy goals came to be.

220
00:09:41,600 --> 00:09:43,401
So if you look, you see love and hate,

221
00:09:43,461 --> 00:09:44,781
the Hall of Echoes, racial skills,

222
00:09:44,801 --> 00:09:46,102
the undead, the shape-shifting mask.

223
00:09:46,482 --> 00:09:48,803
They were all part of this better story ambition

224
00:09:48,843 --> 00:09:51,365
and this ambition of tying narrative mechanics

225
00:09:51,485 --> 00:09:52,965
to the actual story.

226
00:09:53,406 --> 00:09:54,826
And then obviously strategist mode

227
00:09:54,926 --> 00:09:56,267
and the extra skills trees,

228
00:09:56,347 --> 00:09:58,848
those fed into the combat ambitions

229
00:09:59,409 --> 00:10:00,649
and modding and game master mode,

230
00:10:00,709 --> 00:10:02,650
they were all there to supply

231
00:10:02,850 --> 00:10:04,751
the multiplayer vision that we had.

232
00:10:05,817 --> 00:10:06,617
So the future was bright.

233
00:10:07,077 --> 00:10:08,898
Original Sin, Enhanced Edition, Definitive Edition,

234
00:10:08,998 --> 00:10:12,420
sorry, Enhanced Christ, Enhanced Edition released.

235
00:10:12,800 --> 00:10:15,501
It was very successful on PS4 and X1.

236
00:10:16,922 --> 00:10:19,003
We had money, the coffers were loaded.

237
00:10:19,063 --> 00:10:20,764
We had a team, we had four studios.

238
00:10:21,785 --> 00:10:23,686
We had a direction in the form of a demo

239
00:10:23,706 --> 00:10:24,906
which was called the Prospect Demo,

240
00:10:24,926 --> 00:10:27,147
which was the very first version of Original Sin 2.

241
00:10:28,248 --> 00:10:30,329
So it looked as if nothing could go wrong.

242
00:10:31,973 --> 00:10:35,274
All right, so let's start with the story,

243
00:10:35,494 --> 00:10:37,195
which is arguably probably the thing

244
00:10:37,215 --> 00:10:39,856
that went wrong the most throughout the entire development

245
00:10:39,896 --> 00:10:41,817
and had an impact on a tremendous amount of things.

246
00:10:43,418 --> 00:10:45,419
So these are actually the very first

247
00:10:45,519 --> 00:10:46,459
origin stories that we had.

248
00:10:46,739 --> 00:10:49,241
These were present in the prospect point demo,

249
00:10:50,341 --> 00:10:51,782
so the one that we used for Kickstarter

250
00:10:51,802 --> 00:10:53,803
and that we demonstrated to multiple journalists

251
00:10:53,863 --> 00:10:56,464
and which we used to show if you were that person,

252
00:10:56,504 --> 00:10:58,445
suddenly all of the dialogues were going to change

253
00:10:58,885 --> 00:11:00,406
in the game because you became that person

254
00:11:00,446 --> 00:11:01,066
for the game world.

255
