1011
00:42:46,175 --> 00:42:47,856
And the reasoning was, we want to make sure

1012
00:42:47,876 --> 00:42:49,317
that players, when the game ships,

1013
00:42:49,937 --> 00:42:52,679
are going to have new content to play through.

1014
00:42:52,939 --> 00:42:54,920
Otherwise, there will not be any excitement

1015
00:42:54,980 --> 00:42:56,521
if they already consumed all of the content.

1016
00:42:56,801 --> 00:42:58,683
And we had people that kept on playing, playing, playing.

1017
00:42:58,703 --> 00:43:00,524
Like, they had already stacked up hundreds of hours

1018
00:43:00,924 --> 00:43:03,466
just on the very early first act.

1019
00:43:04,506 --> 00:43:07,568
And so the problem was that we were getting a lot of data

1020
00:43:08,269 --> 00:43:08,929
from the

1021
00:43:11,771 --> 00:43:14,752
for Joy from Act One, but we weren't getting any data

1022
00:43:14,792 --> 00:43:15,873
from Act Two and Three.

1023
00:43:17,054 --> 00:43:20,275
So to explain how we got into the problem

1024
00:43:20,295 --> 00:43:22,817
that I'm about to show you, one of our main goals

1025
00:43:23,277 --> 00:43:25,558
with the systems design was that each stat point

1026
00:43:25,858 --> 00:43:27,579
was going to matter, and that the leveling up

1027
00:43:28,079 --> 00:43:31,421
would be a very tangible thing so that you would have

1028
00:43:31,441 --> 00:43:34,082
a continuous desire to improve your character

1029
00:43:34,123 --> 00:43:35,603
and get better equipment and better skills.

1030
00:43:36,985 --> 00:43:39,328
And we had a world with very few bottlenecks,

1031
00:43:39,348 --> 00:43:40,850
so the only way that we could guide you

1032
00:43:40,890 --> 00:43:44,313
was through level scale, no, not level scaling, level gaps.

1033
00:43:44,473 --> 00:43:46,956
So if you were level two and you fought a level four creature,

1034
00:43:47,036 --> 00:43:49,198
it had to be very hard, but we still wanted you

1035
00:43:49,218 --> 00:43:50,820
to have a chance to defeat that creature

1036
00:43:50,860 --> 00:43:51,961
because if you managed to do that

1037
00:43:52,502 --> 00:43:54,064
using the systemics of the game,

1038
00:43:54,384 --> 00:43:55,565
you were going to feel good about it.

1039
00:43:56,399 --> 00:43:59,141
So what we did is we had a very steep leveling curve,

1040
00:43:59,381 --> 00:44:01,062
so it was about 20% per level

1041
00:44:01,502 --> 00:44:03,263
of extra damage hit points and so forth.

1042
00:44:03,983 --> 00:44:07,765
And that meant that you would feel it very, very strongly

1043
00:44:07,825 --> 00:44:08,606
when you went to level up.

1044
00:44:08,966 --> 00:44:10,947
But it also meant that if you were a level too high,

1045
00:44:11,047 --> 00:44:12,948
it was going to be very easy to kill something

1046
00:44:13,068 --> 00:44:13,989
if it was at a lower level.

1047
00:44:14,769 --> 00:44:16,150
And that's the thing that went wrong.

1048
00:44:16,650 --> 00:44:19,111
So this is data that we obtained from early access.

1049
00:44:19,151 --> 00:44:21,072
This is a heat map of where people were walking.

1050
00:44:21,092 --> 00:44:24,173
This is a heat map of where people were dying.

1051
00:44:24,473 --> 00:44:26,094
And so that was really good.

1052
00:44:26,935 --> 00:44:29,696
But we didn't have this information for Act Two and Act Three.

1053
00:44:30,016 --> 00:44:32,177
And so what we did is we invited play testers

1054
00:44:32,197 --> 00:44:35,718
to the company, volunteers, to try things out.

1055
00:44:37,114 --> 00:44:38,736
and we tracked the data from them.

1056
00:44:38,996 --> 00:44:40,818
The problem was that we couldn't find a lot of volunteers

1057
00:44:40,838 --> 00:44:43,000
that were ready to spend two weeks in the studio

1058
00:44:43,040 --> 00:44:44,161
because that was the time you needed

1059
00:44:44,201 --> 00:44:45,302
to play through the entire game.

1060
00:44:46,092 --> 00:44:51,676
So the only data that we could capture was the data that we got from our internal QA.

1061
00:44:52,557 --> 00:44:57,221
And so our internal QA, they know this game very, very, very well.

1062
00:44:57,942 --> 00:45:02,085
So to give themselves an extra challenge, without telling us, they started having parties

1063
00:45:02,225 --> 00:45:03,947
of three characters instead of four characters.

1064
00:45:04,387 --> 00:45:05,268
And they went through the game.

1065
00:45:05,308 --> 00:45:06,829
And then obviously they had a bit of a challenge.

1066
00:45:07,289 --> 00:45:11,673
And so what we never saw was something that became very apparent in the first week of

1067
00:45:11,733 --> 00:45:14,776
release was that the game, if you did everything.

1068
00:45:15,921 --> 00:45:20,628
accrued too much experience, something that hadn't shown up in any of the tests that we

1069
00:45:20,648 --> 00:45:26,116
did before because QA was following their critical paths and we had some runs that tested

1070
00:45:26,156 --> 00:45:29,982
everything but given the amount of time that it took to test all of it, the data never

1071
00:45:30,042 --> 00:45:30,603
really popped up.

1072
00:45:31,773 --> 00:45:34,575
game comes out, our min-maxers start doing everything

1073
00:45:34,655 --> 00:45:35,356
in the entire game.

1074
00:45:35,776 --> 00:45:38,298
By the time they're at the end of act two,

1075
00:45:38,378 --> 00:45:40,579
they're two levels higher than they're supposed to be.

1076
00:45:40,620 --> 00:45:41,980
By the time they're in act three,

1077
00:45:42,301 --> 00:45:44,202
they're way too powerful, they're just breezing through it

1078
00:45:44,242 --> 00:45:45,283
and say, oh my god, boring.

1079
00:45:46,724 --> 00:45:49,446
And that was completely against the design that we had

1080
00:45:49,486 --> 00:45:51,607
where we wanted you to feel every single point

1081
00:45:52,287 --> 00:45:53,728
that we were putting in the level.

1082
00:45:54,109 --> 00:45:55,690
So we panicked, we literally panicked.

1083
00:45:56,250 --> 00:45:58,472
Because we knew how important the leveling curve was.

1084
00:45:59,493 --> 00:46:00,714
And we intervened.

1085
00:46:01,215 --> 00:46:02,736
We released the patch four days later,

1086
00:46:02,756 --> 00:46:04,939
and which we hadn't tested,

1087
00:46:05,540 --> 00:46:06,901
and we just introduced spikes.

1088
00:46:07,602 --> 00:46:10,045
So we just upped the difficulty level

1089
00:46:10,225 --> 00:46:11,147
in the middle of Act Two,

1090
00:46:12,028 --> 00:46:13,069
at the end of Act One,

1091
00:46:13,429 --> 00:46:15,532
and at the end of Act Two, if I'm not mistaken.

1092
00:46:15,612 --> 00:46:17,114
So these are the spikes that you're seeing there.

1093
00:46:18,139 --> 00:46:20,461
It worked, it certainly worked.

1094
00:46:21,101 --> 00:46:23,544
Game became harder and our reasoning was like,

1095
00:46:23,804 --> 00:46:28,088
okay, these are the guys that played through really fast.

1096
00:46:28,128 --> 00:46:28,949
There's a whole bunch of people

1097
00:46:28,969 --> 00:46:30,570
that will play through a lot slower.

1098
00:46:30,991 --> 00:46:33,793
So we're going to test the leveling curve now

1099
00:46:33,914 --> 00:46:35,155
and change it as much as possible

1100
00:46:35,515 --> 00:46:37,617
so that the people that are trailing,

1101
00:46:37,637 --> 00:46:38,638
if you want, through the game.

1102
00:46:39,381 --> 00:46:40,642
are going to have a better experience.

1103
00:46:41,182 --> 00:46:44,224
And so over time we managed to smooth it and round it

1104
00:46:44,284 --> 00:46:45,205
and we solved the problems

1105
00:46:45,245 --> 00:46:46,926
because there were some other problems going on also.

1106
00:46:47,726 --> 00:46:50,808
We got everything sorted out.

1107
00:46:50,889 --> 00:46:52,129
But it was another reminder

1108
00:46:52,149 --> 00:46:53,790
that if you don't visualize your data

1109
00:46:54,131 --> 00:46:56,752
or you don't have enough data to make decisions on,

1110
00:46:57,133 --> 00:47:00,695
it becomes really, really hard to tweak your game.

1111
00:47:02,116 --> 00:47:04,978
Here's another change that came in very late, AI 2.0.

1112
00:47:06,643 --> 00:47:09,805
So we learned from DOS 1 that our combat was very slow.

1113
00:47:10,285 --> 00:47:11,885
People take a lot of time figuring out

1114
00:47:11,905 --> 00:47:13,326
what they're going to do and it's a lot of fun.

1115
00:47:14,566 --> 00:47:16,827
And to make sure that people wouldn't get bored

1116
00:47:16,927 --> 00:47:18,208
as they played the game,

1117
00:47:18,288 --> 00:47:20,989
we tried to make every single combat handcrafted

1118
00:47:21,049 --> 00:47:22,489
and very different to the other combats

1119
00:47:22,509 --> 00:47:23,709
that you were encountering in the game.

1120
00:47:24,490 --> 00:47:29,612
and so the prescribed approach was to make tactical puzzles out of each combat which you could solve

1121
00:47:29,712 --> 00:47:34,153
in many many ways. Now you need to know that the approach that we have to the design of skills was

1122
00:47:34,173 --> 00:47:39,755
to introduce concepts early on then teach players how to combo them and then later on give them some

1123
00:47:39,795 --> 00:47:40,556
skills to top it off.

1124
00:47:41,403 --> 00:47:46,548
And what that meant for the AI was that it was very easy to foresee what players were going to have in the beginning of the game.

1125
00:47:46,989 --> 00:47:48,831
It became much harder in the middle of the game.

1126
00:47:48,851 --> 00:47:53,476
It became almost impossible at the end of the game because we had, I think, close to 300 skills.

1127
00:47:54,497 --> 00:47:58,761
And it's also a classless game, so you can just mix and match any skill that you want.

1128
00:48:00,043 --> 00:48:01,324
So in the past with Original Sin 1,

1129
00:48:01,364 --> 00:48:03,705
we had a very simple primitive state machine

1130
00:48:04,465 --> 00:48:06,166
where it was if-then rules that were made

1131
00:48:06,206 --> 00:48:08,386
by combat designers that were going to decide

1132
00:48:08,426 --> 00:48:09,427
what the AI was gonna do.

1133
00:48:09,787 --> 00:48:11,627
And that meant that if you figured out

1134
00:48:12,748 --> 00:48:15,569
some kind of strategy that was successful against the AI,

1135
00:48:15,809 --> 00:48:16,689
you could keep on doing it

1136
00:48:16,729 --> 00:48:19,790
because probably the combat designer had not applied

1137
00:48:19,810 --> 00:48:22,551
the whole in the AI's thinking throughout the entire game.

1138
00:48:23,651 --> 00:48:26,292
And so in October of 2016,

1139
00:48:28,200 --> 00:48:37,067
So 3.9 a year before release we say you know we maybe should have a real AI. Now uncharacteristically

1140
00:48:37,107 --> 00:48:42,491
so I was against it because I thought it was too risky that we weren't going to manage to get it

1141
00:48:42,551 --> 00:48:46,413
done in time because there was going to be a lot of fiddling with weights and if the approach didn't

1142
00:48:46,433 --> 00:48:47,334
work we had nothing.

1143
00:48:47,915 --> 00:48:49,256
And the other thing that I didn't like about it

1144
00:48:49,276 --> 00:48:51,259
is that it meant that we actually couldn't really

1145
00:48:51,339 --> 00:48:53,181
finalize any of the combats in the game

1146
00:48:53,201 --> 00:48:55,504
until the AI was going to be ready.

1147
00:48:55,684 --> 00:48:57,086
And they told me it was going to take two months,

1148
00:48:57,106 --> 00:48:59,168
but I didn't believe a word of it.

1149
00:48:59,709 --> 00:49:00,290
Rightfully so.

1150
00:49:02,753 --> 00:49:04,815
So this was one of the cases where

1151
00:49:04,956 --> 00:49:06,578
our multi-studio structure is safe today.

1152
00:49:07,425 --> 00:49:09,889
We had a programmer working in Ghent.

1153
00:49:10,129 --> 00:49:12,732
We had one paired with him in Quebec.

1154
00:49:13,053 --> 00:49:15,175
And together, they spent a 17-hour day.

1155
00:49:15,556 --> 00:49:17,859
And so they worked and worked and worked on the AI.

1156
00:49:18,479 --> 00:49:20,001
And by somewhere in January, February,

1157
00:49:20,041 --> 00:49:21,203
we started having something.

1158
00:49:21,603 --> 00:49:23,546
But they did work on it like this

1159
00:49:23,846 --> 00:49:25,368
until the very end of production.

1160
00:49:26,109 --> 00:49:27,630
But AI 2.0 was fantastic.

1161
00:49:27,770 --> 00:49:31,192
It really added to the gameplay that was present in the game.

1162
00:49:31,392 --> 00:49:33,633
There was a whatever strategy you came up with,

1163
00:49:33,673 --> 00:49:37,054
the AI could do something cool against it.

1164
00:49:37,555 --> 00:49:40,256
It was very clever also about abusing glitches in the system

1165
00:49:40,276 --> 00:49:41,717
that we didn't even know that existed.

1166
00:49:41,957 --> 00:49:44,718
Probably the most famous example was the bartender

1167
00:49:44,738 --> 00:49:46,399
that drank all the alcohol to buff himself.

1168
00:49:48,701 --> 00:49:50,822
not dealing with the content because it was in combat, right?

1169
00:49:50,842 --> 00:49:56,846
So, or we had an AI that shot a barrel of oil,

1170
00:49:58,527 --> 00:50:03,030
not, sorry, an AI that shot a barrel of oil to slow you

1171
00:50:04,330 --> 00:50:06,592
while you were hasted to get rid of your hasted status

1172
00:50:06,652 --> 00:50:09,334
and all these kinds of emergent behavior came from the AI.

1173
00:50:09,374 --> 00:50:12,015
So I think it was a very big element in the success.

1174
00:50:12,035 --> 00:50:14,697
So I'm very happy that the programmers that argued for it

1175
00:50:15,097 --> 00:50:17,038
won this particular argument.

1176
00:50:19,457 --> 00:50:23,902
So all of this problems, and there were more,

1177
00:50:23,922 --> 00:50:25,023
but I'm running out of time.

1178
00:50:26,685 --> 00:50:29,208
All of these problems obviously had an impact

1179
00:50:29,748 --> 00:50:33,012
on our release, and in our particular case,

1180
00:50:33,052 --> 00:50:35,014
we had multiple release dates.

1181
00:50:35,594 --> 00:50:37,937
Our very first release date was our Kickstarter,

1182
00:50:38,037 --> 00:50:40,399
because we went to PAX, we went to journalists,

1183
00:50:40,459 --> 00:50:41,981
we released a demo that they could play.

1184
00:50:42,722 --> 00:50:44,606
And that's how we had all of our previews.

1185
00:50:44,686 --> 00:50:46,450
Our second release date was our early access,

1186
00:50:46,490 --> 00:50:47,914
because then we went to the public and we said,

1187
00:50:47,954 --> 00:50:49,658
here's act one of the game that we're trying to make.

1188
00:50:50,680 --> 00:50:52,083
Please play it and let us know what you think.

1189
00:50:52,964 --> 00:50:54,585
Our third release date was internally called

1190
00:50:54,625 --> 00:50:55,665
as Krill release date,

1191
00:50:56,025 --> 00:50:57,246
because somebody had clicked on the button

1192
00:50:58,187 --> 00:50:59,568
to release the game prematurely.

1193
00:50:59,588 --> 00:51:01,269
So this was two weeks before release.

1194
00:51:01,969 --> 00:51:04,010
Luckily, luckily we had a phone number

1195
00:51:04,050 --> 00:51:06,292
from somebody at Valve that we could,

1196
00:51:06,372 --> 00:51:08,993
so that we could call to rectify it rapidly,

1197
00:51:09,013 --> 00:51:10,414
because it would have been a disaster.

1198
00:51:11,775 --> 00:51:13,056
Then we had the actual release date,

1199
00:51:13,276 --> 00:51:15,537
which in our case was plagued by power outage

1200
00:51:15,577 --> 00:51:16,358
in the entire city.

1201
00:51:16,538 --> 00:51:18,739
So we had to do all kinds of stunts

1202
00:51:18,779 --> 00:51:20,060
to get the game actually released.

1203
00:51:21,001 --> 00:51:23,445
And then we had the definitive edition release date

1204
00:51:23,485 --> 00:51:26,550
is when we came up with an improved version of the game,

1205
00:51:27,031 --> 00:51:27,993
which released last year.

1206
00:51:28,694 --> 00:51:31,359
So that was literally the fifth release date for those two.

1207
00:51:32,584 --> 00:51:35,686
Now on release, we paid the price for the word count.

1208
00:51:36,326 --> 00:51:39,288
And the thing, is that on this one?

1209
00:51:39,328 --> 00:51:41,889
I think it's on the next one, yeah.

1210
00:51:42,269 --> 00:51:45,011
We paid the price and that we were review bombed.

1211
00:51:45,451 --> 00:51:48,113
And we were review bombed by very angry people in Russia

1212
00:51:48,533 --> 00:51:50,634
that said, where the hell is my Russian localization

1213
00:51:50,654 --> 00:51:51,214
that you promised?

1214
00:51:51,635 --> 00:51:53,616
And we said, well, it's gonna release on 21st of September

1215
00:51:53,676 --> 00:51:56,337
because the translation companies have suffered some delays

1216
00:51:56,377 --> 00:51:57,818
because somebody has been changing the script

1217
00:51:57,858 --> 00:51:58,719
until yesterday.

1218
00:52:00,303 --> 00:52:03,804
And we haven't talked about translation,

1219
00:52:03,824 --> 00:52:05,084
but those guys were heroes also.

1220
00:52:05,104 --> 00:52:07,685
Because there's translation, there's proofreading.

1221
00:52:07,785 --> 00:52:09,065
And with a game that's this big,

1222
00:52:09,545 --> 00:52:11,226
proofreading takes a long time also.

1223
00:52:13,826 --> 00:52:14,987
And they were angry.

1224
00:52:15,047 --> 00:52:16,667
They were so angry, and you could see it.

1225
00:52:16,687 --> 00:52:18,007
So what we did is we said, you know what,

1226
00:52:18,047 --> 00:52:21,968
we'll just release the beta text, right?

1227
00:52:22,068 --> 00:52:24,489
I mean, you'll see it's a really good translation.

1228
00:52:24,549 --> 00:52:25,889
It's just not 100% finished.

1229
00:52:26,429 --> 00:52:27,270
And that actually worked.

1230
00:52:27,350 --> 00:52:29,410
We went to Twitch in Russia.

1231
00:52:29,890 --> 00:52:32,572
We talked to Twitchers and to calm down the community.

1232
00:52:32,592 --> 00:52:33,952
We said, like, this is what they're doing.

1233
00:52:33,972 --> 00:52:36,253
They had a few problems and this blah and so forth.

1234
00:52:36,273 --> 00:52:36,694
And it worked.

1235
00:52:37,454 --> 00:52:38,515
I would certainly not recommend it

1236
00:52:38,555 --> 00:52:39,935
because we were at that moment,

1237
00:52:39,955 --> 00:52:42,496
we had a 96% user rating on Steam

1238
00:52:42,536 --> 00:52:44,077
and we were, I think we went down to 70

1239
00:52:44,497 --> 00:52:45,178
or something like that.

1240
00:52:45,598 --> 00:52:47,919
So we were suffering very, very, very hard.

1241
00:52:48,219 --> 00:52:49,260
But it was our own fault, of course,

1242
00:52:49,280 --> 00:52:50,880
because we changed so many things.

1243
00:52:52,601 --> 00:52:52,821
So.

1244
00:52:54,748 --> 00:52:55,909
If you hear all of this, you would say,

1245
00:52:55,929 --> 00:52:57,170
well, what a disaster, right?

1246
00:52:57,250 --> 00:53:00,252
But there's a couple of things that you need to realize

1247
00:53:00,292 --> 00:53:01,453
when you think about Originals Sin 2.

1248
00:53:01,493 --> 00:53:04,334
This is a 120-hour game that was made in two years' time.

1249
00:53:05,195 --> 00:53:07,596
So that is, I think, quite an achievement of the team.

1250
00:53:08,217 --> 00:53:11,119
And it was a game that went really right

1251
00:53:11,159 --> 00:53:12,720
because it scored very, very highly.

1252
00:53:13,120 --> 00:53:14,241
It sold very well also.

1253
00:53:14,301 --> 00:53:16,242
It's still in the charts to this date.

1254
00:53:17,603 --> 00:53:20,184
So, and it was a testimonial that all of that iteration,

1255
00:53:21,009 --> 00:53:24,691
and all that of the refusal of compromise on quality

1256
00:53:24,871 --> 00:53:27,973
that it paid off, even if it caused a few production

1257
00:53:27,993 --> 00:53:28,333
problems.

1258
00:53:29,774 --> 00:53:33,096
So my lesson was that not compromising on quality

1259
00:53:33,456 --> 00:53:34,037
is a good thing.

1260
00:53:34,257 --> 00:53:36,258
But you need to figure out how the hell you're

1261
00:53:36,278 --> 00:53:37,759
going to make your production work with it,

1262
00:53:38,019 --> 00:53:39,100
because otherwise, you're going to keep

1263
00:53:39,180 --> 00:53:40,180
on running into problems.

1264
00:53:40,240 --> 00:53:41,601
And it's problems that you don't want to have.

1265
00:53:42,361 --> 00:53:44,002
So what are the big takeaways that we've

1266
00:53:44,042 --> 00:53:46,024
applied to our own processes on the next things

1267
00:53:46,044 --> 00:53:46,684
that we're working on?

1268
00:53:47,537 --> 00:53:48,998
and which also not all work.

1269
00:53:50,218 --> 00:53:52,340
So first thing is documentation.

1270
00:53:53,300 --> 00:53:56,282
Balance and documentation for a big RPG is really important.

1271
00:53:56,702 --> 00:53:59,404
You're gonna spend, you're gonna create thousands of pages

1272
00:53:59,444 --> 00:54:01,545
of documentations for QA, for your scripters,

1273
00:54:01,765 --> 00:54:02,846
even the briefs of the writers.

1274
00:54:03,406 --> 00:54:04,767
So you have to figure out a way

1275
00:54:04,947 --> 00:54:06,748
of not having too much documentation

1276
00:54:06,788 --> 00:54:08,109
because the less documentation you have,

1277
00:54:08,149 --> 00:54:09,470
the easier it is to maintain it.

1278
00:54:09,830 --> 00:54:11,811
On the other hand, you have to be able to inform everybody

1279
00:54:11,852 --> 00:54:13,192
about what's supposed to be going on.

1280
00:54:13,232 --> 00:54:14,713
So you need to have sufficient documentation.

1281
00:54:15,133 --> 00:54:16,814
This is a very, very hard problem.

1282
00:54:16,994 --> 00:54:18,595
If anybody knows a perfect solution for it,

1283
00:54:18,635 --> 00:54:20,776
please come tell me.

1284
00:54:21,276 --> 00:54:21,916
White boxing.

1285
00:54:21,956 --> 00:54:24,017
White boxing refers to the,

1286
00:54:24,517 --> 00:54:26,298
how do you make a game that you can review

1287
00:54:26,598 --> 00:54:29,759
without having to put all of the production values in there?

1288
00:54:30,359 --> 00:54:32,220
It turns out that for a game like Original Sin 2,

1289
00:54:33,281 --> 00:54:39,971
it's very complicated. We've often observed that if a level design is not far enough and

1290
00:54:40,091 --> 00:54:44,778
decorated enough, a scripter is not going to put effort in making all of the permutations that he

1291
00:54:44,818 --> 00:54:46,681
needs to do. And that is...

1292
00:54:48,704 --> 00:54:52,087
Yeah, that is a very surprising thing. We've fought against this, but we never solved it.

1293
00:54:52,127 --> 00:54:57,051
So, figuring out a good white-boxing process, and I think we have one now, is very important.

1294
00:54:57,412 --> 00:55:02,796
Automation. Invest in automation as much as you can. It is the saving grace when you're iterating.

1295
00:55:03,196 --> 00:55:06,539
I mean, because if you don't have to have a human going through everything, and you have something

1296
00:55:06,559 --> 00:55:09,041
that can automatically test your game, you're going to save so much time.

1297
00:55:10,531 --> 00:55:12,271
Your processes need to be built for iteration.

1298
00:55:12,291 --> 00:55:13,492
You need to tell people up front,

1299
00:55:13,512 --> 00:55:14,432
this is what we're going to be doing.

1300
00:55:14,492 --> 00:55:16,373
We're going to change until the end, right?

1301
00:55:16,773 --> 00:55:18,733
If you don't do it, you will have a lot of frustration,

1302
00:55:18,753 --> 00:55:19,613
you'll have a lot of fights,

1303
00:55:20,034 --> 00:55:21,334
and you can avoid a lot of these fights

1304
00:55:21,374 --> 00:55:22,854
by just being very open about it.

1305
00:55:23,675 --> 00:55:25,675
Yeah, the two-minute cook syndrome, I think that's obvious.

1306
00:55:26,315 --> 00:55:27,996
You need to have some dictatorship involved

1307
00:55:28,076 --> 00:55:30,837
in making a game, but you still have to open up the lines

1308
00:55:30,857 --> 00:55:32,397
so that people can understand what you're saying.

1309
00:55:33,896 --> 00:55:35,458
Feedback loops, we talked about that.

1310
00:55:35,839 --> 00:55:36,740
Invest heavily in it.

1311
00:55:37,080 --> 00:55:37,821
It's very important.

1312
00:55:39,002 --> 00:55:40,183
Real world circumstances.

1313
00:55:40,384 --> 00:55:41,685
We saw a few examples of that.

1314
00:55:42,927 --> 00:55:44,689
Hard to organize, but definitely worth it.

1315
00:55:46,130 --> 00:55:47,492
But topic on its own.

1316
00:55:49,114 --> 00:55:49,894
Never stop improving.

1317
00:55:49,914 --> 00:55:52,437
That's the thing that we really did well, I think,

1318
00:55:52,718 --> 00:55:53,739
and it paid off for us.

1319
00:55:55,145 --> 00:55:57,427
And then you have to accept that iteration takes time.

1320
00:55:58,188 --> 00:55:59,289
There's nothing to be done about it.

1321
00:55:59,449 --> 00:56:00,990
You're never gonna get it right from the first time.

1322
00:56:01,490 --> 00:56:05,153
If your production is completely production focused,

1323
00:56:05,934 --> 00:56:07,976
then you will lose opportunities to make your game better.

1324
00:56:08,196 --> 00:56:09,317
I think that when you make a game,

1325
00:56:09,337 --> 00:56:11,018
you should strive to make it as good as you can.

1326
00:56:11,618 --> 00:56:13,460
And sometimes you have to just take risks.

1327
00:56:13,500 --> 00:56:14,981
And they can blow up in your face.

1328
00:56:15,021 --> 00:56:16,963
I had one blow up in my face this morning, actually.

1329
00:56:18,464 --> 00:56:20,265
More to be said about that probably in the next weeks.

1330
00:56:23,207 --> 00:56:25,389
And then, yeah, visualize.

1331
00:56:25,449 --> 00:56:26,429
Visualize as much as you can.

1332
00:56:27,010 --> 00:56:28,911
Make sure that you can see data,

1333
00:56:28,931 --> 00:56:30,272
that you can see disasters happening

1334
00:56:30,312 --> 00:56:31,333
like the word count that we had.

1335
00:56:32,113 --> 00:56:32,994
And yeah.

1336
00:56:34,075 --> 00:56:37,800
So these were the top things that we used to change our processes.

1337
00:56:38,220 --> 00:56:43,427
Whether or not they work, we'll see in the next postmortem, but that's going to be it for today.

1338
00:56:43,467 --> 00:56:45,309
